  "prompt": "How do train drivers know which way to go on tracks?",
  "response": "Train drivers know which way to go on tracks through several key methods:\n\n1. Signaling systems\n- Colored signals along the track indicate stop, proceed, speed limits, etc.\n- Different signal colors and positions give specific instructions\n\n2. Track switches and points\n- Mechanical switches physically change track direction\n- Dispatchers or signal operators control these remotely\n- Drivers are informed about which route they should take\n\n3. Route maps and schedules\n- Train drivers have detailed route maps showing track layouts\n- Scheduled routes are predetermined before departure\n\n4. Radio communication\n- Dispatchers give instructions about track routes and potential changes\n- Drivers communicate with central control for guidance\n\n5. GPS and computerized tracking systems\n- Modern trains use computer systems to track location and route\n- Electronic displays show current track and recommended path\n\n6. Track circuits and electronic tracking\n- Electronic systems monitor train positions and track occupancy\n- Help prevent collisions and ensure correct routing\n\nThese methods work together to ensure trains travel on the correct tracks and follow safe, predetermined routes.",
